Quoted By: >>58097828 >>58098008
>>58097212
There is still some passenger rail service in the US but since the Second World War it has never been as popular as it was before. The US government subsidizes a passenger rail line called Amtrak. They have to subsidize it because not enough people use it for the fares to pay its expenses.

I think that with the rise of interstate bus lines in the US after the war, rail travel has come to be perceived as being as slow as bus travel, with all the associated inconveniences, while being almost as expensive as air travel. This is a cultural difference from Europe, but one at least partially grounded in the physical size of the US. If you live in an urban area on the east coast of the US, and you want to travel to California for a vacation, train travel will take, using the very optimistic figures from the official schedules, between thirteen and twenty hours, by the fastest available express routes, and cost more than a six-hour trip by air. The same trip by bus is 60-80+ hour ordeal in a cramped, smelly, vandalized metal box full of methheads and people who just got out of prison, that has no bathroom, and depending on the bus line may cost almost as much as air fare. It is a popular meme in the US to blame the decline of train travel on automobile ownership, but this kind of trip isn't very practical in an automobile either. The sheer scale of distance involved makes air travel the obvious choice, especially when you can get plane tickets for less than train tickets.

But here. Have a fox on a train.
